In Lucretius' De Rerum Natura we have, so far as the subject matter goes, nothing more than an exposition of the theory of Epicurus, but in the intense seriousness with which the poet points out the practical bearing of the creed and its great importance for the conduct of life, the tone of the work is essentially Roman3 and it is to this very Roman element that it owes its tremendous vigor of presentation, its glowing portrayal of the blessings of Epicureanism.
